included.description:
As a UX Research Intern, I planned, implemented, and executed user research studies that would have a direct and significant impact on the design and function of one of Salesforce's products. During my internship I conducted two major research studies. The first was an exploratory research study collecting interview data that would be used to determine user needs and direct the future of the product. The second, most significant project was a full end-to-end summative benchmark usability study.

For the benchmark usability study, I created 15 tasks which tested the fundamental functions of the product, coordinated and communicated with product stakeholders and designers to validate the tasks, recruited participants, and conducted 90-minute (remote) sessions with 8 Salesforce customers. I then analyzed the 12+ hours of video data (using Morae usability software) under stringent time constraints, extracting usability metrics such as time-on-task, error rates, success rates, post-test perceived task ease/difficulty, and post-session System Usability Scale (SUS) survey data. I also collected qualitative data about points of confusion and delight with the product and suggestions for improvement and new features. The final product of this research study was a plethora of video data (8 participant videos broken into 15 task segments, accompanied by highlight and lowlight reels) and a final presentation of the usability findings (including participant video clips) which received high praise for being useful, pertinent, and easily understood.
included.title: User Experience Research Intern

included.description:
As a graduate research assistant, I employed the user-centered design process to enhance the user experience of a web-based interactive data visualization software for the National Science Foundation (NSF) titled Deep Insights Anytime, Anywhere (DIA2). I was the lead UX researcher/designer on the team, responsible for managing projects, leading brainstorming sessions, overseeing deadlines, and facilitating collaboration between teams. 

As a graduate teaching assistant, I aided in a course titled "Principles of UX Design" which teaches undergraduate students the foundational elements of the user-centered design process.
included.title: Graduate Research and Teaching Assistant

included.summary:
I am a user experience researcher at Salesforce in Indianapolis, IN. My primary objective is to ensure that users and customers of Salesforce Marketing Cloud are at the center of our products. I'm passionate about creating experiences that enable, excite, and empower people.

I graduated from the Purdue University College of Technology in December, 2015, receiving my Master's in Human-Computer Interaction from the department of Computer Graphics Technology. My thesis examined the intersection of user experience, social media, technology, and marketing. 

I graduated with distinction from the Purdue University Brian Lamb School of Communication in December of 2013, receiving a Bachelor's degree in Communication - Public Relations and Rhetorical Advocacy, minoring in Organizational Leadership and Supervision. 

During my undergraduate career at Purdue, I was employed as a social media strategist for the Purdue University Department of Computer and Information Technology. I also have experience as a digital marketing specialist, working with Challenge Systems, a high-performance wireless technology company.
included.headline: User Experience Researcher at Salesforce
